## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
complexity
## Location
src/auto_learn.rs:319-338 (compute_file_relationships)
## Violation
```rust
fn compute_file_relationships(&self) {
    let files: Vec<&String> = self.session_files_modified.iter().collect();
    if files.len() < 2 { return; }
    for i in 0..files.len() {
        for j in (i + 1)..files.len() {
            if let Err(e) = self.db.save_file_relationship(files[i], files[j]) { ... }
        }
    }
}
```

`session_files_modified` is a `HashSet<String>` with no cap. A long-running session that edits 1000 distinct files triggers ~500K `save_file_relationship` calls at `on_session_end`. Each call is a SQLite INSERT — at typical 100 µs per write, that's 50 seconds of synchronous DB work on session close, with the user waiting at the terminal.

Combined with `prune_old_data`'s cap of `MAX_FILE_RELATIONSHIPS = 500`, the pruning thereafter throws away ~99.9% of the work just performed. The two functions silently contradict each other: pair generation is O(N²), prune is O(N) keeping K rows, and the net useful output is bounded by K regardless of how much work was paid.
## Mandated refactor
Cap `session_files_modified` at e.g. 50 entries (LRU eviction in `handle_file_write_success`). Or: batch the INSERTs into a single transaction (`self.db.batch_save_file_relationships(&pairs)` with `BEGIN..COMMIT`). Or — best — replace pairwise edges with a per-session relationship "session_id, file_path, modified_at" log and compute co-edit similarity at query time via a JOIN, sidestepping the N² blow-up entirely.
